)
This error occurs because Docker Desktop is attempting to execute its proxy binary inside your Ubuntu WSL distribution, but the file or mount path (/mnt/wsl/docker-desktop/...) has lost its executable permissions or is encountering a conflict with WSL's metadata mounting.

The core error is right here:

execvpe(/mnt/wsl/docker-desktop/docker-desktop-user-distro) failed: Permission denied

Here is a step-by-step guide to fix it, ordered from the easiest workaround to the most permanent solution.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution 1: The Quick Reset (Fixes temporary mounting glitche)
Often, the virtual networks or shared mount paths between Docker and WSL get locked up. A clean restart of both services usually resolves this.

Quit Docker Desktop completely (right-click the Docker icon in your system tray and select Quit Docker Desktop).

Open Windows PowerShell or Command Prompt as an Administrator and shut down WSL completely:

DOS
wsl --shutdown
Restart Docker Desktop. It will automatically spin up your Ubuntu WSL integration again.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution 2: Fix Executable Permissions Manually
If the file permissions actually got altered, you can manually grant execution rights back to the Docker binaries from inside Ubuntu.

Open your Ubuntu terminal.

Run the following command to force-grant executable permissions to the Docker Desktop mount folder:

Bash
sudo chmod -R +x /mnt/wsl/docker-desktop/
Restart Docker Desktop.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution 3: Fix WSL Mount Options (wsl.conf)
------------------------------------------------
If you have custom mount settings in your wsl.conf, it might be stripping away execution permissions (noexec) from shared Windows drives or custom mounts.

In your Ubuntu terminal, open your configuration file:

Bash
sudo nano /etc/wsl.conf
Check if you have an [automount] section. Ensure it allows standard metadata and execution permissions. It should look like this (or you can add it if it's missing):

Ini, TOML
[automount]
enabled = true
options = "metadata,exec"
Save and exit (Ctrl + O, Enter, then Ctrl + X).

Run wsl --shutdown in PowerShell and restart Docker Desktop.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution 4: Clean Re-install of Docker WSL Components
------------------------------------------------------------
If the proxy binaries are corrupted, you can force Docker to recreate them by toggling the integration.

Open Docker Desktop Settings (the gear icon).

Navigate to Resources > WSL integration.

Uncheck "Enable integration with my default WSL distro" and uncheck Ubuntu.

Click Apply & restart.

Once restarted, go back to the same menu, re-check Ubuntu, and click Apply & restart again.

This forces Docker to re-inject clean, correctly-permissioned wrapper binaries back into your Ubuntu distribution.

